<br>
All our holidays... they're there to celebrate or honor something.  How many people do you think really celebrate that particular something?<br>
<br>
Like... July 4th... It's Independence Day.  It's a day to celebrate our Independence from Britain, to honor the people who long ago fought &amp; died to give us the freedom we enjoy today, and to praise the courage our founders had in implementing such a radical (at the time) system of government which I personally think is among (if not <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>the</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->) best system of governments in the world today.<br>
<br>
But how many people do you think actually think about any of that on July 4th?  I bet a lot of people celebrate that they get to blow shit up with fireworks.  A lot of people celebrate a night out with the family.  Etc.  I'm not saying people shouldn't celebrate... just wondering how many people actually give thought to <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>why</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> they're celebrating.  <br>
<br>
I don't think it's very many.  I wonder if commercialization of the holidays is part of the problem.  Here in Seattle... it's not called Independence day... or even the Fourth of July.  Know what it's called?  Fourth of Jul-Ivar's... Ivar's is a seafood restaurant.  200 years ago people were risking, and losing their lives to win freedom from Britain... and we've renamed the celebration in spirit of a Seafood restaurant.  I mean... did I miss something in history class where Captain Ivar pulled off a daring tactical maneuver by firing fish &amp; chips at British soldiers, thus distracting them in combat?<br>
<br>
But I also wonder if maybe, we just don't really care.  We celebrate the celebration and that's it.  Our independence is just the excuse to celebrate.<br>
<br>
Memorial day is there to honor the people who've died in our world wars, right?  But the only people I saw at the cemetary were some older veterans, probably honoring lost companions.  Everyone else was celebrating the day off work... the pool opening... start of summer...<br>
<br>
Labor day is there to honor the labor unions who fought to make the workplace something other than legalized slavery.  But again, it's pretty much billed as an end of summer blowout... get all your partying out of the system cuz you gotta wait for the next Memorial day for more barbecues.  It's funny... cuz you can pretty much flag which companies treat their employees like crap by seeing who makes their employees work on Labor Day when not in a critical business (hospitals and so forth... <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>points finger accusingly at Blockbuster video</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->).<br>
<br>
Or maybe... maybe it's not so nefarious, and we as people just have some subconcious pagan need to celebrate the changing of the Seasons.  Is it coincidence that our most actively celebrated holidays are so close to Summer/Winter Solstice and the Vernal/Autumnal Equinox?  Maybe people just have a need to celebrate the start of Summer and they can do it w/o calling down the wrath of the Chuch this way <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .<br>
<br>
Anyways, not really <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>news</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, just something I was thinking about.<br>
<br>
- Syll<br>
<br>
PS: I can't believe they renamed our Independence day after a freaking seafood restaurant, regardless of whether or not they gave money towards the fireworks display <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=traelle>Traelle</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.cpmission.com/graphics/icons/icon22.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle><font color=#993366>Prettier than Kuladen<br>Used to be Sar</font></span><br>  Posts: 513<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/1/03 11:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=539.topic&index=1>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://sarshouse.homestead.com/files/images/sartrae.gif height=191 width=143></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How we celebrate our holidays...</span><hr size=1> I never thought about the 4th of July as anything but fireworks, until my exhusband, when we lived in North Carolina, took me to a revolutionary war cemetary.<br>
<br>
Then, I got to thinking about the fact that, buried below my feet, were men, and boys who DIED, so that I know the lifestyle I know. So that I don't understand what having a monarch is like, so that I can worship how I choose.<br>
<br>
Since then, I give a private salute to those men, and all who've come since, on the 4th.<br>
