A lot of unions have a &quot;strike fund&quot; used to help support the workers that are out on strike. Also, we are notified when a local union is having a strike so we can offer support, money and food to those workers affected. <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Explain how it is Legal to have a Union shop, where in order to work there you MUST be a union member or able to join the union in 6 months, but it is illegal to have a non union shop, were the union is excluded.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Not sure if this is a state thing...but where is it illegal to have a non-union shop??? First of all, in order to have either an open or closed shop, the majority of the workers there had to petition the Department of Labor and have a vote of the workers in order to certify the Union as their sole bargaining representative. If the workers at some shop decide they don't want the Union in there anymore, they would have to sign a petition to the Department of Labor to de-certify the Union. A vote would be ordered and conducted by the Department of Labor, and the majority rules. <br>
Seems to me your biggest beef is with the workers that refuse to decertify their unions. Why don't they do that? Because unions have afforded them decent living wages and benefits. Unions fight for workplace safety and make sure the companies abide by OSHA regulations. Sorry to tell you this, Twotribes, but big businesses would abuse their workers a hell of a lot more if it wasn't for Unions fighting for decent working conditions. Even shops that are non-union benefit from the hard work and blood spilled by unionists by establishing safety standards. Without safety standards and worker's compensation benefits, big businesses would tell the injured worker &quot;Sorry you got hurt, but we're firing you&quot; and replace that person with a healthy worker that they can abuse.<br>
Twotribes, if you don't believe in unions, don't go work at a union job. Let the rest of us enjoy the benefits that were so fought for by our unionists before us.<br>
