<br>
I do think you have something there with the seasonal celebrations.  July 4th is High Summer.  Thanksgiving is the Harvest Festival.  Christmas is the Winter Festival.  Easter is the Spring Rites.  To the *day* we have things like Halloween and May Day settling on &quot;heathenish&quot; celebrations, that celebrate the *very* pagan aspects of said days.  Christmas is also much like Yule, and Easter like Ostara.  There are certain &quot;rituals&quot; of form - holly and painted eggs - but mostly celebrations were not for &quot;rememberance&quot; but togetherness over all - and except for the commercial bits, that's what we do now.<br>
<br>
On the slight divergence...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Not sure if this is a state thing...but where is it illegal to have a non-union shop???<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I think he's talking about the fact that companies and/or a minority of anti-union workers have no rights to exclude unions from their businesses, but shops that have voted to have unions have the right to force new hires to join said union.  That seems bass ackwards to me.  I have nothing against unions in general, but closed shops are *wrong*.  You should never be able to force someone to join an organization (union) just to work at a seperate organization (the company.)<br>
<br>
Frankly, while unions had their uses in days of yore in fighting the ridiculously disgusting workplace dangers and low wages, now they are more hinderance than help.  (Or, at least, they have been at the three companies I've worked at.)  I'll I've seen of modern unions are strikes that last for years, putting my friends and their parents into poverty and debt...blatant lies about companies and individual members of management on shoddy recruitment material...threats made by union campaigners (often bright eyed extremist liberals from the local university) toward both high level management and common laborers who seem uninterested (including threats of violence) and a whole host of other problems.<br>
<br>
Juliet, I don't mean personal offense.  I realize that my personal experiences with unions are not necessarily typical of all the rest.  However, while you are correct in saying that unions began the trend toward workplace safety, they no longer have much to do with it.  The government now does all of that work - including OSHA and workman's compensation.  Laws exist thanks to the work of unions years ago that prevent those abuses from happening again, but OSHA investigates non-union shops just as much as the union ones.  *shrugs*  Unions complicate matters from my view from the Human Resources office.  It's so much easier when someone in &quot;management&quot; can talk to a &quot;worker&quot; directly about problems without worrying about a mediator all the damn time.  As someone who studies and teaches communication, it's always been obvious to me that third parties just get in the way. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=vampiricmuse>Vampiric Muse</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Blood is sexah ;)</span><br>  Posts: 306<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/3/03 1:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=539.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How we celebrate our holidays...</span><hr size=1> teaching Unions are so full of shit its not funny.<br>
