David- same goes for you. You have said in the past that you are a teacher. Are you in a unionized teaching job? If so, then you are the ultimate hypocrite. There are plenty of private schools that pay low wages to teachers that you could teach at that aren't unionized.<br>
As for the safety issues- Unions are still fighting for new ergonomic standards and other safety issues. Carpal Tunnel Syndrome is something that has been around a long time, but fairly recently it has been recognized as a repetative motion injury. You have big businesses out there that hire physicians to contravert those cases. Those same physicians will argue that Carpal Tunnel Syndrome is caused by a lack of nutrients in your diet! As technology advances, more is discovered about repetative motion injuries. As new ergonomically correct equipment is being invented, it's the Unions that are forced to push the issue and make employers invest in newer, safer equipment for the employees. OSHA comes in at the enforcement stage. But it's the unions that are still setting the standards.<br>
Safety isn't the only issue that unions address. They also address equal pay for equal work, discimination, and a whole lot of other issues that are still problems in the workplace today. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.insight.rr.com/kindredwolf/Shaila2.gif " style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jullietstarshooter>julliet starshooter</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 58<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/3/03 12:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=539.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How we celebrate our holidays...</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Unions complicate matters from my view from the Human Resources office. It's so much easier when someone in &quot;management&quot; can talk to a &quot;worker&quot; directly about problems without worrying about a mediator all the damn time. As someone who studies and teaches communication, it's always been obvious to me that third parties just get in the way. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I agree with you in theory, but it doesn't work in the real world that way. The problem comes in when &quot;management&quot; tries to break the Collective Bargaining Agreement with the &quot;worker&quot; and reneg something provided for in the Collective Bargaining Agreement. The third party you refer to is the Union representative, who will &quot;get in the way&quot; when management tries to break the terms of the Collective Bargaining Agreement. The workers, by vote, have elected the union as their sole bargaining agent. If management has nothing to hide, then they should be freely sharing whatever information they wanted to share with the employee to the union. If management does have something to hide, then thank God those workers have a union there to protect them. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.insight.rr.com/kindredwolf/Shaila2.gif " style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=eliezeroferudin>Eliezer of Erudin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Order of Crimson Hands</span><br>  Posts: 1528<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/3/03 12:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=539.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How we celebrate our holidays...</span><hr size=1> The only problems I have with Unions are distinctions drawn between what is Union Labor and what is not.  I've never worked a Union job, but I'm not a rich executive or bureaucrat either.  There are times and places where Unions are positive, and some where they hinder the process.  But such is the way of things. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile