<br>
I'm not sure I agree with that at all.  It only takes one or two disgruntled employees to get the ball rolling.  The business I worked for (a hotel) had fine benefits, fair wages, etc.  But there were a few people who had a bone to pick with management, and decided to organize.  And it's pretty easy to get the less educated employees who might not speak the language so well to go along with things when you promise them MORE MONEY, whether it is realistic or not.<br>
<br>
As far as it being decided by a majority vote, that was not the case in our situation.  If I recall correctly, a majority of the employees was not required, just a majority of those who turned out to vote, which was a very low percentage of our actual employee base.<br>
<br>
And this is not to say that all unions are bad, because there are businesses and industries that definitely need that kind of regulation.  My experiences though, have not been positive ones.<br>
