<br>
And my intent is not to union bash.  But am I getting the wrong impression, or are you assuming that all unions are working for the greater good of the employees?  When it boils down to it, they are businesses as well, and therefore, the possibility exists that they are doing what is in THEIR best interest, not the employees.<br>
<br>
The union I dealt with gave me the impression of a bunch of used car salesmen.  And I wasn't the only one who felt that way.  And after all was said and done, many of our employees (not all of them of course) ended up making less money due to their union dues. Some made more, some made less, and everyone (employees and employers) had to work under a new, more rigid set of rules.  Maybe some thought that was good...but most didn't.<br>
<br>
I'm sure there are many unions fighting the good fight against companies who take unfair advantage of their employees.  Maybe I'm just lucky to live in a state (California) with a fairly strict labor code for employers, and a decent system for employee recourse against companies who violate labor law.<br>
